ernment studies estimate that the agency loses up to  billion in tax revenue each year because of cost basis errors your broker will send form b to the irs each sale of a stock bought in  will generate a b you will get a copy the irs will get a copy on that b form the gain or loss will be characterized as longterm or shorttermthe key here is to make sure your broker uses the accounting method you prefer as they report gains or losses most brokerages report individual securities using the fifo method as that is the irs default method fifo is an acronym for “first in first out” – that is the shares bought first are the shares sold first with the fifo method you end up selling your cheapest shares first in a down market that’s okay – but in a rising market many investors favor the specific id method in which they identify specific shares they want to sell using this method enables you to sell your highestcost shares first which can be taxwise more details worth noting according to the wall street journal the new reporting rules will also apply to reits foreign stocks and foreign etfs classified as stock in  in  the reporting rules will apply to most etfs and drips in addition to mutual funds in  the reporting requirements may also apply to derivatives and partnerships remember this does not apply to shares  investments bought before  you will still have to personally track the cost basis of these investments and report the realized gains and losses to the irs by the way these new irs reporting rules do not apply to taxsheltered investment accounts such as  plans and irashave any questions feel free to give us a call at  or send us an email at infohochmanandbakercomthese views are those of peter montoya inc and do not necessarily represent the views of the advisor and should not be construed as investment advice this information should not be construed as investment tax or legal advice please consult your advisor for further information all information is believed to be