the actual tax returns the irs encourages you to keep federal tax returns until the period of limitations expires this is the time period you have to claim a credit or refund or the time frame they have to levy additional taxes on you state returns should be saved for the same time period in most cases you are safe to toss them after  yearsif you plan to claim a credit or refund after you file then you should retain relevant tax records for  years if you claim a loss from worthless securities or bad debt deduction you should keep related records for  years employment tax records should be held for  years after the date the tax becomes due or paid whichever is laterfor most investments and banking statements the yearend statement is the most important if you have any investment liquidations that generated capital gains or losses you will want to keep the statements related to those transactions investment purchase information should be kept at least until the cost basis and purchase date is reflected on your account statements those figures will be used in future gainloss calculations real estate documents including closing statements mortgage information and expenses incurred to improve the property should be kept as long as you own the property once the property is sold keep documents showing the deed recording and the mortgage payoff receipt it is also advisable to hold onto those receipts for  years after you sell exchange or liquidate any real propertyif you make any contributions receive distributions or rollover any iras or other qualified plans you’ll need to document those transactions the irs wants to make sure they receive any taxes due and will penalize violations keep your annual k statements and any form  nondeductible contributions to traditional iras form  contribution information or form r distributions you receive while roth iras are funded with aftertax dollars you need to keep those records until you are  ½ and have had the account for at least  yearsif you anticipate needing to apply for medicaid you’ll want to keep fairly complete financial history documentation medicaid has a fiveyear lookback period in many states so to qualify for aid you have to prove that you didn’t transfer any assets except those specifically allowed medical records and medical insurance documents should be held onto for about  years from when services are rendered if the medical expenses are claimed on your taxes however you’ll want to keep them for  years following the year they are claimedlife insurance policy information should be kept for the life of the policy plus  yearssmall business owners will likely need to keep any payroll documents for at least  years should there be a lawsuit or a legal dispute involving your company or one of its employees a detailed financial history would be helpfulas a reminder it’s a good idea to shred any documents you’re disposing that have personal information on them social security numbers active account numbers etc and while you’re sorting through all your files who knows – you may uncover some new projects that need attending to like updating your powers of attorney or completing a household inventory for your insuranceif you have any questions feel free to give us a call at  or send us an email infohochmanandbakercom posted by hochman cole investment advisors inc at  am no comments thursday march   how long to keep those documentsthis is the time of year when we all start thinking about income taxes as you wade through your piles of receipts and various statements you may question which documents need to be saved and for how long although there is no one hard and fast rule there are some guidelines which you can follow that may free up a little space in your file cabinetsas a general rule the irs suggests retaining records for  years following the year in which expenses are claimed on your tax return the standard irs audit only goes back  years however the irs has six years to challenge your return if it seems you under reported your gross income by  or more for most investments and banking statements the yearend statement is the most important if you have any investment liquidations that generated capital gains or losses you will want to keep the statements related to those transactions investment purchase information should be kept at least until the cost basis and purchase date is reflected on your account statements those figures will be used in future gainloss calculationsreal estate documents including closing statements mortgage information and expenses incurred to improve the property should be kept as long as you own the property once the property is sold keep documents showing the deed recording and the mortgage payoff receiptif you make any contributions receive distributions or rollover any iras or other qualified plans you’ll need to document those transactions the irs wants to make sure they receive any taxes due and will penalize violations if you anticipate needing to apply for medicaid you’ll want to keep fairly complete financial history documentation medicaid has a fiveyear lookback period in many states so to qualify for aid you have to prove that you didn’t transfer any assets except those specifically allowedas a reminder it’s a good idea to shred any documents you’re disposing that have personal information on them social security numbers active account numbers etc and while you’re sorting through all your files who knows – you may uncover some new projects that need attending to like updating your powers of attorney or completing a household inventory for your insurancehave any questions feel free to give us a call at  or send us an email at infohochmanandbakercom posted by hochman cole investment advisors inc at  pm no comments friday october   ira consolidation are you missing out on a chance to make your life simpler are you one of the many americans who has several retirement accounts were some of these rolled over from previous employers and held in a variety of places have you had years where you almost forgot about one or two of these accountsconsider consolidating your current ira accounts into a single account with your financial adviser you’ll find that eliminating multiple accounts may reduce fees charged by institutions for holding these iras makes monitoring performance easier and allows your financial adviser to take a more comprehensive approach to managing your portfolio in addition a consolidated account will make matters much clearer when you begin to take your required minimum distributionsremember to also speak with your financial adviser about any k plans you may still have with former employers these can be rolled into your ira which may provide many more options for investing as a selfdirected ira you will have access to a multitude of investment choices whereas most company plans offer less than twenty these additional options allow you to choose how you invest your money based on your individual preferences ie risk level expense costs exposure to specific industries time frames etc while company k plans have strong selling points such as company matching provisions when you are no longer working for that company they vanish the benefits of iras are numerous and are especially favorable to the alternative of keeping a plan with a former employer not only can a selfdirected ira be more easily coordinated with your other financial holdings but your beneficiaries have more flexibility with an ira beneficiaries of iras usually have the option to stretch receipt of distributions over their lifetimes and consequently the corresponding taxes but most company plans do not allow this option when stretch iras are not allowed a beneficiary will be required to take a lump sum distribution and pay income tax on the entire amount in that tax year this can be a tremendous burden and reduces the net inheritance considerably also if you are currently contributing to a k plan another option for you to consider is taking an inservice distribution although limited by the provisions of the plan these inservice distributions allow you to roll money from your company’s plan into your selfdirected ira which will provide you with more investment options for that qualified money it’s common for individuals to have too heavy a weighting of their employer’s stock in the k plan while company loyalty is admirable it is often wise to roll a portion of that holding out of the plan into an ira and reallocate to reduce risk it’s worth your time to think about consolidating your iras talk to your financial adviser and make sure you’ve considered your alternativesthis information is not meant as tax or legal advice please consult your financial adviser or a tax professional for more informationhave any questions feel free to give us a call  or send us and email infohochmanandbakercom posted by hochman cole investment advisors inc at  am no comments labels k inservice distribution ira required minimum distributions retirement plan rollover selfdirected ira tuesday march    college savings plans have you heard about the study conducted by the department agriculture expenditures on children by families they have been tracking the cost of raising a child since  and report that a twoparent middleincome family can expect to spend  they estimate from  to  per year for  years to raise a child born in  this figure is not adjusted for inflation nor does it include any college costs with the costs for raising a child so high a lot of people wonder how they can possibly afford to save money for their child’s education even if you can’t save a lot of money your children or grandchildren can still benefit greatly from a college savings plan one of the more popular ways to save for college is a  college savings plan these savings plans are managed by investment firms or state government agencies and provide a tax advantaged way to save for higher education a  savings plan is flexible—you can open a  plan for anyone a child a grandchild a friend and there are no income limits you can contribute up to   for married couples a year without gift tax consequences plans are administered by individual states but investors may choose any plan regardless of where they live also you can pay for educational expenses at any eligible institution not just schools in the state of the plan the tax advantages are the major draw for  plans the main tax advantages are that the principal grows taxdeferred and the distributions for qualified educational expenses are exempt from tax qualified educational expenses include tuition fees book supplies and equipment required for study at any accredited college university or vocational school the money can be used for room and board as long as the beneficiary is at least a halftime student if a distribution from a  plan is not used for a qualified education expenses then it is subject to income tax and possibly a  early distribution penalty though contributions are not deductible for federal income tax purposes many states provide state income tax deductions to find out more about saving for college check out this website that has tools for calculating college costs and more information on  and other college savings plans httpwwwsavingforcollegecom to see the study expenditures on children by families by the department of agriculture visit httpwwwcnppusdagovpublicationscrccrcpdf this information is not meant as tax or legal advice please consult your financial advisor for more information have any questions feel free to give us a call  or send us an email infohochmanandbakercom posted by hochman cole investment advisors inc at  am no comments labels beneficiary college tax rules friday february   roth ira conversions in  what’s new for starting in  the  modified agi adjusted gross income limit for conversions to roth iras is eliminated also married taxpayers filing separate returns can now convert amounts into a roth ira for conversions in  any amounts required to be included in income are included in income in equal amounts in  and  you can elect to include the entire amount in income in benefits of conversionthe main difference between traditional ira and roth iras is the way in which the contributions and distributions are taxed contributions to traditional iras are tax deductible however you must pay taxes on the distributions contributions to roth iras are made on an aftertax basis and consequently you do not have to pay taxes on that money again distributions are tax free after age  ½ as long as you have had the roth ira for five years this is an attractive option for young investors as they will mostly likely be in a higher tax bracket in retirement than they are now however roth iras are not just for the young older investors can benefit from conversion to a roth especially if they do not have an immediate need for their ira assets if you name your spouse as the beneficiary of your roth ira your spouse can treat hisher inherited ira as their own and heshe will not be required to take withdrawals this provides an opportunity for further compounding for the rest of your spouse’s life then your spouse’s beneficiary a child or grandchild for example and heshe can then take withdrawals according to their life expectancy all the while the assets continue to compound tax freenote if you made aftertax contributions to your traditional ira then that portion of the total contributions can be distributed taxfree in the case of a conversion the tax on the ira assets would be solely on the portion of the beforetax contributionsconversion drawbacksa conversion from a traditional to a roth ira is a taxable event you can pay taxes on the conversion amount out of the ira or with outside funds however if you are under  ½ paying the tax from the ira would result in a  penalty the good news as mentioned above is that you can divide the taxes between your  and  tax returns consult your financial advisorbefore you arrange for any rollover or conversion it is a good idea to consult a financial advisor each person’s financial circumstances are different and any tax consequences should be fully understood before any action is taken this information is not meant as tax or legal advice please consult your financial advisor for more informationhave any questions feel free to give us a call  or send us an email infohochmanandbakercom posted by hochman cole investment advisors inc at  pm no comments labels ira retirement plan rollover roth tax rules older posts home subscribe to posts atom welcome to hochman cole hochman cole investment advisors inc is an secregistered investment advisor committed to helping our clients improve their longterm financial success our customized programs are designed to grow and conserve our clients’ wealth by delivering an unprecedented level of personalized service h  b is located in northbrook il blog archive ▼    ▼  february  the fiscal cliff legislation key provisions for ►    ►  january  ►    ►  july  ►  april  ►  march  ►    ►  october  ►  march  ►  february  ►    ►  december  ►  october  ►  august  ►  july  ►  june  labels k  beneficiary  college  company stock  daily benefit amount  estate planning  inservice distribution  ira  legacy  long term care  medicare  promotion  required minimum distributions  retirement plan  rollover  roth  selfdirected ira  social security  stretch ira  tax rules  website  links hochman  baker website google finance search this blog   hochman cole investment advisors inc increases stake in chevron corporation cvx headlines manchester united make fresh move for bale following zidanes comments lt q net profit jumps  pc to rs  crore stock market opens lower as wall street resumes tech selling morgan stanley reaffirms equal weight rating for nuvasive inc nuva oppenheimerfunds inc takes position in silver bay realty trust corp sby soda tax to hit wallets aug  preckwinkle crude oil prices plunge